{"/service/ndnp/ohi/batch_ohi_honeysuckle_ver01/data/sn87075277/0034058014A/1949040701/0730.xml":{"full_text":"1,\nThursday, April 7, 1949\nA NEWSPAPER IN AND FOR CALDWELL AND NOBLE COUNTY\nPUBLISHED EVERY THURSDAY AT CALDWELL, OHIO\nAn Independent Democrat newspaper that goes into the homes\nof Noble County and covers the Caldwell business zone like the\nsunshine.\nC. J. ESTADT\u2014Publisher L. L. LONG\u2014Sports Editor\nJ. D. WHEELER\u2014Editor FLORENCE ORR\u2014Society Editor\nOffice: 309 Main Street Telephone 98\nRATES OF SUBSCRIPTION\nOutside Noble County\u2014One Year $2.25 Six Months $1.25\nNoble County and Radius\u2014One Year $1.50 Six Months .75\nEntered at the postoffice at Caldwell, Noble County, Ohio, as\nsecond class mail matter under Act of Congress of March 3, 1870.\nMember of Ohio Newspaper Association, National Editorial\nAssociation, Audit Bureau of Circulation, Ohio Weeklies, Inc., Ohio\nPress News Service, and the Newspaper Advertising Service, Inc.\nTHE RECESSION\nAccording to the research department of the federal re\nserve bank of Cleveland, the postwar boom reached its high\nwater mark around the end of last October when the com\nbined output of the nation\u2019s factories and mines was the\ngreatest in peacetime history. According to the same yard\nstick, the recession is now only about five months old. Dur\ning those five months total production declined about four\npercent from the record high.\nThe transition from boom to recession, however, did not\noccur over a short weekend last fall. The current downturn\ndid not emerge suddenly nor quite unexpectedly. In some\nrespects the readjustments has been under way for two or\nthree years. Conversion to more natural peacetime com\npetitive conditions has been a staggered process and as a\nconsequence, not all of the necessary readjustments will\nhave to be accomodated at the same time.\nWhile business activity on the whole tended to expand\nalmost continuously for a period of nearly three years, as\nearly as 1946, the night-club and cafe business, for example,\nwas deflated to a more normal level by a decline in patron\nage. Certain types of house furnishings such as floor and\ntable lamps also quickly ran into a period of over-produc\ntion and sluggish demand.\nThe following year or 1947 was characterized by a widen\ning of the readjustment phase. Although business on the\nwhole was better thah the year before, a more significant\nnumber of businesses began to feel the end of the boom.\nIh Noble county the prices of farm and food products\nwere in a definitely downward trend by August, 1948, when\nthe probabilities of a bumper harvest were increasing day\nby day. By February of 1949 that decline had gone so far\nas to suggest that not much more deflation in agricultural\nprices is immediately in sight. Stability in grain prices\nover the next few months would mitigate whatever indus\ntrial inventory liquidation is necessary.\nThe sharpest cut in the new car fields was announced\nthe past week by Kaiser-Frazer. This would indicate that\nautomobile industry is finally headed into a period of\njjp^dm^tment to normal competitive conditions and the pro\ncess Should be noticeably less painful because of the piece\nmeal realignments that have been taking place more or less\nbehind the scenes during the past three years.\nTHE NEW SALES TAX BILL\nIn the state assembly .last week, Sen. Emmet R. Guthrie\nof Coshocton, who represents Noble county from this sen\natorial district, introduced a bill to substitute a simple gross\nsales tax for the present retail system.\nUnder the present set-up, about nine,cents out of every\nten reaches the state treasury... The loss ys probably greater,\nfor with all the leaks any conclusion must be partly guess\nLwork. One of the best characteristics of Senator Guthrie\u2019s\nqplan is that it would produce additional millions for the\nstate without costing individual taxpayers much if any more\nthan they pay now.\nIt is designed to rid us of the existing complicated\nsystem of stamps, discounts, commissions and redemptions\n\u2014a burden tolerated by no other state in the union.\nThe expense of the method we are now using is terrific.\nThere is the cost of printing stamps, the three per cent dis\ncount at which merchants buy them, the commission al\nlowed various agencies for handling them and the revenue\nlost through redemption of the stamps.\nIn addition, nobody knows just how much is lost nor\nmally through tax evasion but it must be enormous for the\nsystem offers plenty of chances for trickery.\nSenator Guthrie is familar with the system for he\nheaded this tax district, with headquarters in Zanesville, for\nnine years. His plan is one to get more state revenue with\nout placing new burdens on the people.\nThe state needs more money and his bill tops anything\nwe have seen to date for accomplishing this purpose.\nTHE POET\u2019S CORNER\u2014\nABSENT\nWILLIAMSON\nW W MEW TRIH-1FE ALbFUtl FURNACE-\nFurnace Inspection. Expert repair\nwork on any make of furnace. Cost\nbased on labor and materials used.\nPhone or write today.\nyears,\ntears\naway,\nDear One, I cannot face the future\nThe loneliness and pain, the bitter\nI shed when\u2019er I think that you\u2019re\nIt seems I miss you more, Dear, every day.\nThough friends are kind and do their best to cheer\nThis path that\u2019s left for me to walk alone\nTheir friendship means so little to me, Dear,\nIf I can\u2019t walk close to your side, My Own.\nI stand beside the grave wherein you rest,\nThis heart of mine is filled with bitter pain\nI try to understand that God knows best\nThough longing just to see you once again.\nIf I could only see you once again\nAnd clasp your hand as I was wont to do,\nIt seems to me that it would ease the pain\nTo clasp my hands in prayer again with you.\nBut God still sends\nAnd winter follows summer as of old\nYet though my life seems more of loss than gain\nI patiently await as years unfold.\nWhen comes the sunset of life\u2019s stormy day,\nEach hearxt will rest beyond the harbor bar\nAll pain and sorrow will be swept away\nAnd blessed peace will reign in realms afar.\nthe sunshine and the rain\nMinnie Ross Mackie\nLimited to Just One Fuel?\nSee the New ALL-FUEL\nFurnace That Burns Coal,\nOil, Gas or Coke\nSince the New Williamson Tripl-ife\nAll-Fuel Furnace was introduced,\nthousands have junked their old one\nfuel heating plants. On farms, in cities\nand small towns, this furnace has re\nmoved, for all time, heating worries.'\nSee it today. Monthly payments to suit.\nFURNACES CLEANED\nCaldwell Htg. Plbg\nWAYNE WILEY, Dealer\nPhone 174-M\nCALDWELL, OHIO\nTHE AMERICAN WAY\nA Headache No Doctor Can Cure\nST\u2019\nDuring this past week in Wash\nington the spotlight of publicity\nhas been turned on the question\nof public health. So diverse is the\nopinion on the question that not\nonly congress, but the medical\nprofession itself has been split\nwide open. Indications now are\nthat the congress may take some\naction\u2014for instance, to provide\nfor more hospitalization, medical\ncenters and other essentials of\nthe proposed measures but\nthere is little chance of a meet\ning of the minds in this session\non the highly-controversial sub\nject of compulsory medical in\nsurance.\nPublication, only recently, of a\nplan approved and sponsored by\nthe American medical association,\nwhich has, until this year, denied\nthere was need for such a plan at\nall, has stimulated discussion and\nbrought to a focus the state of\nthe nation\u2019s health and the ques\nion of what to do about it. Is this\nquestion a matter for private\nsolving? Should it be done with\nstate and local funds, if at all?\nShould it be done with federal\nfunds, plus the private compul\nsion of an insurance plan?\nThere are already three impor\ntant measures in the congress.\nSenate bill No. 5, signed by five\nsenators the Cellar bill in the\nHouse (HR 345) and the Dingell\nbill in the house (HR 783). The\nlatter bill is almost identical with\nthe senate bill. Both are admin\nistration bills. The AMA bill is\nscheduled for introduction soon.\nThe principal difference in the\nAMA measure and the adminis\ntration bills is that the adminis\ntration bills provide for finance\nof hospitals and training of new\nmedical personnel with govern\nment grants and of compulsory\nhealth insurance with a three per\ncent payroll tax split one and\none-half per cent from the em\nploye and one and one-half per\ncent from the employer.\nThe AMA bill contemplates fi\nnancing the measures with local\nand state funds almost exclusive\nly and a voluntary private health\ninsurance plan, similar but less\ncostly than the Blue Cross or\nother similar plans.\nThe fact that the federal gov\nernment already is spending\nsomething like two billion dol\nlars annually for health services,\nincluding the veterans\u2019 adminis\ntration costs, is speeding up the\nplans to adopt a program which\nthe proponents say will bring\nabout better health conditions\nNEWS JOR WAR\nVeterans training under the GI\nbill\u2014as well as their schools and\ntraining establishments will\nhave less paper work to do undei\u2019\na simplified reporting system\nwhich went into effect April 1,\nveterans administration has an\nnounced.\nUnder the new system, VA no\nlonger requires monthly progress\nreports for veterans in job-train\ning establishments. Information\npreviously furnished VA in these\nmonthly reports will be incor\nporated in the report of earnings\nwhich veterans submit to VA\nevery four months.\nSchools below the college level\nalso will report progress and con\nduct of veteran students on this\nVA report of earnings. As in the\npast, colleges and universities\nwill not submit reports of con\nduct and progress, except to no\ntify VA in cases of those students\nwhose conduct or progress has\nbeen unsatisfactory.\nVA emphasized that schools\nand training establishments\nshould continue to report promp\ntly the discontinuance of any vet\neran from training. Veterans are\nurged to make certain the requir\ned reports of earning reach the\nVA regional office handling their\nand eliminate much of the pres\nent spending. Whether this is\ntrue remains to be seen. The fact\nis, however, that congress is vi\ntally concerned about the state of\nthe nation\u2019s health. Surveys show\nthat on any given day there are\napproximately seven million\nAmericans absent from their\nwork due to illness or -some other\ndisability, a tremendous drain on\nearning power and production.\nThe social security administra\ntion says the cost to the nation as\na result of this absenteeism to\nillness is about 27 billion dollars\nannually.\nThe president\u2019s committee on\nnational Employ- the Handicap\nped week, which is October 2-8,\nis conducting a national essay\ncontest among secondary school\nchildren, offering $2,000 in prizes\nand closing April 30 of this year.\nAny student in the 11th or 12th\ngrade in public or private school\nis eligible. Sources of informa\ntion concerning the contest are\nstate offices of employment serv\nice and vocational rehabilitation\nand local offices of the civil serv\nice commission and the veterans\u2019\nadministration. Judges of the\ncontest are Mrs. Eleanor Roos\nevelt, Secretary of Labor Maurice\nTobin and the United States com\nmissioner of education.\nTestimony before the house\npostoffice committee on the pro\nposed postal rate increases said\nwere \u201cpunitive\u201d and would cause\ndeficits. Principal witnesses the\npast week included many maga\nzine publishers, including Walter\nD. Fuller of the Curtiss Publish\ning company and A. E. Winger of\nthe Crowell Collier company.\nThey claimed the proposed in\ncrease of second class rates would\ncost their companies more than\ntwice the amount of their profits\nin the first year and more later\non.\nAccording to old-timers here,\nthere is every indication on Capi\ntol hill that despite the existence\nof the work and recommenda\ntions of the Hoover commission,\nit will not be adopted by con\ngress. Instead, there is every\nlikelihood that congress will give\nthe president authority to make\nhis own suggestions for better\nment of the government agencies.\nThe president, however, is known\nto favor many of the proposals\nand suggestions of the Hoover\ncommission.\nVETERANS\ncases before the tenth of the\nmonth following the date the re\nports are due. Failure to submit\nreports in time may result in de\nlayed subsistence checks, VA\nsaid.\nAs a result of this new and\nsimplified reporting system, VA\nfield officers will process at least\nfive million fewer forms a year,\nwith an appreciable savings in\nclerical work.\nQuestions and Answers\nQ. I interrupted my training\nunder the GI bill and now would\nlike to resume training at once\nalthough in a different school.\nMay I go back to classes anytime?\nA. Before you resume your\ninterrupted training, you should\nget a supplemental certificate of\neligibility from VA.\nQ. As the widow of a World\nWar I veteran, I desire to file my\napplication for a widow\u2019s pension.\nMust I file it in the city where\nmy late husband died?\nA. No. The application may be\nfiled through your nearest VA\noffice.\nFrom June 1947 to April 1948\nNaval and Marine Reserve avi\nators flew 487,359.9 pilot hours.\nTHE JOURNAL CALDWELL OHIO\n1 u~ k1 -T-TT!2\nBRIEFS OF TEN YEARS AGO.\nRalph Thompson, better known\nas \u201cTommie\u201d, prominent young\nman of the Berne community,\nhas been appointed liquor inspec\nItor, grade four, and left Mon\nday for Columbus for a weeks\nschooling in the state department\nColumbus C. McAtee and his\nwife, Mary Tilton McAtee, who\nlast September observed 64 years\nof wedded bliss, will again join\nin the celebration of his ninetieth\nbirthday anniversary on Monday,\nApril 10 and her eighty-third\nbirthday on Thursday, April 6.\nDeaths\u2014William G. Crow, 80\nJack Hesson, 24, Mt. Ephraim\nDavid W. Bamfield, 82, Reiners\nville Mrs. Pearl Davison Mills,\nTrinidad, Colo. Mrs. Harry\nHopps, Summerfield Robert F.\nHill, 87, Barnes Ridge.\nSummerfield Mr. and Mrs.\nJones Easley and daughter, Jean,\nof Dover and the former\u2019s mother\nand step-father, Mr. and Mrs.\nAlva Wharton, returned recently\nfrom a trip through the southern\nstates.\nLEGISLATIVE\nNOTES...\nBy GEORGE C. PHILPOT\nMonday evening the House was\nvisited by a host of Granges.\nThey visited with various mem\nbers before the session, and then\nrepaired to the gallery in time\nfor the opening of the session. I\nfailed to see anyone from Noble\ncounty but met Mrs. Gilliland\nand Mr. Gant from Morgan\ncounty. Mrs. Gilliland is well\nknown in both Brookfield and\nRenrock communities. Mr. Gant\nis a grandson of Albert Gant\nwho is a brother of Homer Gant\nof Marion township.\nThe Grangers were introduced\nby a member and given an ova\ntion.\nTwo bills were \u201claid on the\ntable\u201d or informally passed by\nrequest of the authors, due to\nerror or duplication.\nThe House passed two bills, H.\nB. No. 210, which provides for\nthe employment and status of\nsubstitute teachers and H. B. No.\n236, which relates to the termin\nation of a teacher\u2019s contract by\na board of education. This bill\npassed 97 to 24, takes the word\n\u201cgross\u201d out of the teacher tenur\nbill when it states that contract\nof a teacher found guilty of\ngross neglect or immorality, by\nthe board, may be terminated. I\nwas really surprised because of\nthe particular people who spon\nsored the bill as well.as the ar\ngument put up by some people\nwho call themselves friends of\nthe teachers.\nTuesday afternoon some school\nand groups of Granges were in\ntroduced from the floor.\nFive bills and one resolution\nwere passed, but only three af\nfect Noble county. H. B. No. 328\npermits jail matrons to receive\nup to $200.00 a month if approv\ned by the common pleas judges.\nOf course, the money will not\nbe available in many small\ncounties. I did not support the\nbill.\nAnother bill, Am. H. B. No.\n238, requires various officers in\nthe state to report to the attorn\ney-general actions when taken\nfavorable to the state of Ohio\nrelative to certain claims.\nThe third bill, Am. H. B. No.\n107, places the quail on the game\nlist with a provision that they\nwill be propagated for ten years\nwithout any privilege of an open\nseason. This will encourage the\nuse of hunting license money to\npropagate the quail. In ten\nyears, we should be able to tell\nwhether or not the quail popula\ntion can be increased, or whether\nor not they will gradually be\ncome extinct like the passenger\npigeon.\nWednesday, the crowded gal\nleries witnessed one of the most\ntumultous sessions in the history\nof the general assembly.\nAfter passing two bills, H. B.\nNo. 325 and H. B. No. 344, rela\ntive to policemen\u2019s pension fund,\nthe House passed to the real bus\niness of the day, which was the\nF. E. P. C. bill, H. B. No. 106.\nThis bill which has been dis\ncussed pro and con for several\nweeks, sets up a commission of\nfive to investigate, prosecute and\nrender decisions in the matter of\ndiscrimination in employment\ndue to race, creed or national or\nigin.\nSeveral amendments were of\nfered from both, sides of the\nHouse, some were adopted and\nothers failed. The paragraph ex\nempting religious, fraternal and\nsocial organizations were delet\ned. Another permitting employ\ners to ask applicants whether\nthey belong to any party or\ngroup advocating the overthrow\nof our government by force was\nadopted. Another amendment\nAlmost 25 per cent of all men,\nwomen and children, or approxi\nmately one out of every four, are\nbeing kept either wholly or in\npart, by some form of govern\nment relief it was revealed today.\nBirths\u2014A daughter to Mr. and\nMrs. Joseph Ickes, Caldwell,\na son to Mr. and Mrs. Frank Mc\nAuley, Caldwell route 3 a son\nto Mr. and Mrs. William Cun\nningham, Olive.\nMarriages\u2014Mary Belle Wick\nham, Fredericksdale, and Jasper\nKhune, Pleasant City John Ver\nba, Pleasant City, and Lillian La\nfollette, Pleasant City.\nG. L. Bond, Mt. Ephraim, has\nbeen employed as teacher in the\nWills rural school system and has\ntaken up his duties as instructor\nof English and Latin in the Old\nWashington high school.\nPlans have been perfected to\norganize for farm bureau dis\ntricts, each with a director, in\nNoble county, patterned after the\norganization now functioning in\nKennonsburg in the eastern sec\ntion.\nstruck out paragraph (b) of Sec\ntion 3, which forbade employers\nto ask an employee or applicant\nabout his color, creed or nation\nal origin or ancestry. The em\nployer, by this amendment, may\nplace questions regarding race,\ncolor, creed or national origin on\napplications, and publish or an\nnounce a preference based on\nrace, color, creed or national or\nigin.\nMany speeches were made,\ntension was great and tempers\nflared due to the debate and the\nrulings of the Speaker.\nThe high point of the debate\nw\u2019as an oration by Mr. Anderson,\nof Franklin county. He stated\nthat he was a Democrat and a\nCatholic and that he had done a\nstretch in the Navy during the\nlast war. Although he was under\ntremendous pressure from his\nparty leaders and because his\nchurch leader in Columbus, Bish\nop Ready, had endorsed F. E. P.\nC., he made the most effective\nspeech against the bill. He read\nthe prayer offered by a rabbi\nwho, as a chaplain, helped dedi\ncate the cemetery at Iwo Jima.\nMr. Anderson\u2019s speech was made\nin an effort to get the House to\naccept a substitute bill which\nwould handle the whole matter\nas an educational project. I agree\nwith his views. His attempt\nfailed by a vote of 66 yeas, 67\nnays because three or four Dem\nocrats were persuaded to change\ntheir vote, and the Speaker also\nvoted.\nThe bill finally passed by a\n.vote of 70 to 61.\nWednesday evening, the House\nEducation committee recom\nmended Am. H. B. No. 24 for\npassage. This bill attempts to\nprevent \u201cbootlegging of pupils\u201d\nby a district from a neighboring\ndistrict. The library bills will be\nstudied next week after a sub\ncommittee submits its report.\nThe committee did approve H. B.\nNo. 25, which is a library bill.\nFrank Ward, whose wife is the\nformer Vivian Reed, of Summer\nfield, represented the Library\nAssociation.\nThe telephone bill, relating the\nnumber of patrons on one line,\nwill be given another hearing\nnext week.\nThe Dunn bill, prohibiting both\na husband and wife to work for\nthe State of Ohio, was recom\nmended for passage. This was\nprobably only a gesture of Cour\ntesy. The author of the bill has\nchampioned this legislation for\nyears but has failed to eet it ap\nproved. The House passed this\nbill a few years ago, but I am\ntold that was only a gesture of\nkindness to the old gentleman,\nwho is a bachelor. The Senate\nkilled the bill.\nThursday the House had to de\nlay convening because the long\nsession on Wednesday delayed\nthe printing company in their\ndelivery of the calendar and the\nJournals.\nSub. H. B. No. 234 amends the\nmunicipal off-street parking bill\nof two years ago by deleting the\ntwo-year time limit. Under the\npresent law, municipality must\ndispose of the land acquired for\noff-street parking after holding\nit two years.\nAm. H. B. No. 308, which reg\nulates the handling, sale and dis\ntribution of barbiturates (sleep\ning pills) was passed.\nMr. Hawkins, of the Ohio\nPower Company, Cambridge, at\ntended the Wednesday session.\nHe visited back of the rail for a\nshort time.\nMr. A. D. St. Clair, of the\nState Department of Education,\nwho is in charge of the study of\npossible redistricting of schools,\ndiscussed some of the problems\nof southeastern Ohio with me on\nThursday.\nI shall be at the court house\npart of the weekend.\nCOMPLETE AUTO SERVICE\nALL MAKES\nBARNHOUSE\nCHEVROLET COMPANY\nTelephone 261 Miller Street\nthe CAPITAL\nCAPPING...\nWith BEN HAYES\nColumbus\u2014In America, April\nis always circus month. Red\nwagons roll northward, gay pen\nnants flutter atop bright new\ncanvas and hearts skip many\nbeats as wild animals roar and\ndaredevil aerialists swing thru\nthe air with the greatest of ease.\nRingling Bros, and Barnum\nBailey, the greatest show on earth\nopened last night in New York\nCity. It will show in Madison\nsquare garden many nights be\nfore pitching canvas in Boston\nand Philadelphia. This is the tra\nditional opening. Then the Big\nOne will open its summer-long\ntour through the vast country. By\nthe time wheat is in shocks,\nRingling Bros., will be reaching\nOhio\u2014Columbus, Zanesville, and\nperhaps Wheeling and Parkers\nburg in West Virginia.\nColumbus had its first circus\nlast week. The Achbar Grotto\nstaged its annual indoors circus\nin the coliseum at the state fair\ngrounds. It was a good show, fea\ntured by baby elephants and hi\nlarious clowns.\nOur first canvas will go up on\nApril 30. Mills Bros., a truck out\nfit, will show at the Mound-street\nlot. This circus has experienced\nadverse publicity in recent years\n\u2014but new management claims it\nis out this season to redeem it\nself. k\nCole Bros, has the Mound-st.\nlot reserved for May 15. This is\nalways a good show. It\u2019s elephant\nherd is large. The show wintered\nin Louisville, Ky., and Columbus\nis always one of its first stops.\nBev Kelley, my friend from Dela\nware who once was Ringling\u2019s\nhead press agent, is working for\nCole Bros., this season.\nThe Ringling show, so spectac\nular it has no equal, skipped\nOhio last season. We were disap\npointed. The Ringling show had\nswung through Canada, toured\nthe West, then showed through\nthe South before going into win\nter quarters at Sarasota, Fla., in\nDecember.\nRingling has not applied here\nyet for a permit\u2014but the inform\nation is that it will make Colum\nbus in late June or ealy July.\nWe can expect a complete\nchange in show. The theme this\nyear is based on the segments\nof the zoodiac. The planting signs\nwill be featured in the \u201cspec\u201d\nthe big parade will be gay with\ntwins, the goat, the fishes, the\narcher and all the other signs\nthat people plant potatoes,\nflowers, pickles and turnips by.\nAnd no doubt the sad clown\n(Emmett Kelly) who always\nrides the end will display a green\nI thumb.\nI think Noble county people\nhave always relished circuses. I\nhave been told that Ike Hayes,\nmy grandfather, and George\nEichhorn saw most of them. This\nlove of circuses began far back\nin the days before circuses used\nwagons to transport animals. I\nhave been told that elephants,\ncamels and other animals once\nwere led up and down the creek\nroads as circuses moved from\ntown to town.\nI\nI\n___________~ Page One\u2014B\nWISE or\nOTHERWISE\nBy E. O. BOND\nThe virtue of a man ought to\nbe measured not by his extra\nordinary exertions but by his\neveryday conduct.\nThere\u2019s always one fellow in\nan organization that can be des\ncribed in a very few words.\nLife is like a mirror we get\nbest results when we smile at it.\nDid you hear about the lady\nschool teacher who was so mod\nest she wouldn\u2019t put an improper\nfraction on the blackboard?\nIt means better health to pay\nyour bills and let your mind have\na rest.\nToo many people quit looking\nfor work when they find a job.\nNo one was ever better than\nhe tried to be.\nSome people grow under res\nponsibility, others merely swell.\nMen live longer now than they\nonce did. They have to meet the\ninstallments.\nThe greatest area of unem\nployment in the world is the re\ngion just above the ears.\nThe wages of sin never go un\npaid.\nGod deserves more than skim\nmed milk from the cream of\nyour earnings.\nPrayer is the key to the day\nand the lock of the night.\nVII soon need NFZ\nI\u2019m a good, sturdy chick. I\u2019ve got\negg production in my blood. Qivel\nme good feed and care from now till'\nhousing time and I\u2019ll show you some\nhonest-to-goodness laying.\nI\u2019ll need your help, though, to\nprotect me from coccidioeis, the\nworst chick killer known. Other\nwise I may be a dead loss.\nIt\u2019s easy for you to stop coxy.\nJust feed me NFZ, the new Dr. Hess\nproduct (1 lb. to 100 lbs. of mash\nfor 4 or 5 days). NFZ contains\nnitrofurazone, the amazing chemical\nmade from farm wastes.\nN Z is very active against coxy\ngerms, stops coxy without slowing\na chick\u2019s growth, and costs only\nhalf as much as the sulfas commonly\nused. Besides, you don\u2019t have the\nbother of dosing at repeated inter'\nvals.\nAll in all, NFZ rates higher as a\ncoxy treatment than the sulfas.\nCosts less than 1/ a chick. Get\nNFZ at\nGIVE HER A LANE HOPE CHEST\nThe Perfect EASTER GIFT\nNo. 2210\nAs advertised in LIFE and LOOK\nBuy Her LANE CEDAR HOPE CHEST Now\nSay '\u2019You\u2019re mine, forever\u201d with\nthis intimate love-gift. It\u2019s the\nonly pressure-tested Aroma\nTight Chest in the world, with\nLane\u2019s exclusive patented fea\ntures. Free moth insurance pol\nicy with every Lane Chest.\n/DEAL GIFT FOR SWEETHEART,\nSISTER, DAUGHTER, MOTHER\nEASTER SPECIAL!\n$4995\nWHILE THEY\nLAST\nBuy Now While\nSelections Are Complete!\nPAY A LITTLE DOWN..\nA LITTLE EACH WEEK!\nLANE\nQUALITY FURNITURE SINCE 1925\nMurphy Furniture Store\nPhone 128-J\n303 Main Street Caldwell, Ohio\nHOPE CHE5T","height":"26751","width":"21261"}}
